In src/adapters/base.py _replace_managed_section() line 332-333: when HARNESSSYNC_MARKER is found in `existing` but HARNESSSYNC_MARKER_END is absent (end_idx == -1), the else branch returns `f"{existing.rstrip()}

{managed}"`. This leaves the orphaned start marker in the output. On the next sync, the start marker is found again, end marker is still missing, and another copy of `managed` gets appended — endless duplication. Fix: replace the else branch at line 332 with `before = existing[:start_idx].rstrip(); return f"{before}

{managed}" if before else managed` to strip the dangling marker.
